    "correct": "A",
    "explanation": "In classic galactosemia (GALT deficiency), excess galactose is reduced by aldose reductase to galactitol in the lens. Galactitol cannot exit the lens and causes osmotic water influx → cataracts. Galactose-1-phosphate accumulation causes hepatotoxicity and brain damage, but galactitol specifically causes cataracts. Positive reducing substance + negative glucose oxidase = galactosuria (not glucosuria).",
    "pearl": "Galactosemia: galactitol → cataracts (osmotic); galactose-1-P → liver/brain toxicity. Urine: positive reducing substance, glucose-oxidase negative. Treat: eliminate galactose (soy formula).",
    "optionExplanations": {
      "A": "Galactitol is the specific metabolite responsible for cataract formation in classic galactosemia. When GALT (galactose-1-phosphate uridylyltransferase) is absent, galactose cannot enter the Leloir pathway to be converted to UDP-galactose for metabolism. Excess galactose accumulates and is diverted to the aldose reductase pathway, which reduces galactose to galactitol using NADPH. Galactitol accumulates in the lens (and other tissues with high aldose reductase activity) because it lacks a transport mechanism for exit — it becomes osmotically trapped. The accumulating galactitol draws water into the lens fibers, causing swelling, protein aggregation, and the characteristic \"oil-droplet\" cataracts of galactosemia. These cataracts can be detected on slit-lamp examination as early as the first week of life.",
      "B": "Galactose-1-phosphate (gal-1-P) is the toxic metabolite primarily responsible for hepatocellular damage and CNS toxicity in classic galactosemia, not cataracts. When GALT is absent, galactose-1-phosphate (produced by galactokinase from galactose + ATP) accumulates in the liver, brain, and red blood cells. In the liver, gal-1-P inhibits phosphoglucomutase and other metabolic enzymes, causing hepatocellular injury, conjugated hyperbilirubinemia, and eventually cirrhosis. In the CNS, gal-1-P is neurotoxic, causing intellectual disability and speech delay. The cataracts, however, are specifically caused by galactitol — not gal-1-P. The distinction between the organ-specific toxic metabolite (gal-1-P → liver/brain) versus the osmotic lens metabolite (galactitol → cataracts) is a classic USMLE discrimination.",
      "C": "UDP-galactose is not a toxic metabolite — it is the normal metabolic end-product of the GALT reaction (combining galactose-1-phosphate with UDP-glucose to produce UDP-galactose + glucose-1-phosphate). In classic galactosemia, the GALT enzyme cannot catalyze this step, so UDP-galactose cannot be produced from dietary galactose. UDP-galactose is actually an essential substrate for glycoprotein and glycolipid synthesis. While cells can synthesize some UDP-galactose via epimerization of UDP-glucose, the block in GALT causes deficiency of UDP-galactose for these pathways, contributing to some galactosemia manifestations. UDP-galactose accumulation (rather than deficiency) does not occur and is not the mechanism of cataracts.",
      "D": "Glucose-6-phosphate is a metabolite in glycolysis (glucose → G6P by hexokinase) and the pentose phosphate pathway. It has no direct mechanistic relationship to galactose metabolism or cataract formation in galactosemia. Galactosemia affects the Leloir pathway of galactose metabolism, not the glycolytic pathway. This distractor tests whether students can distinguish different metabolic pathways by incorrectly suggesting that competition between glucose-6-phosphate and galactose metabolism could cause cataracts — there is no such mechanism. The cataract-causing metabolite is specifically galactitol, produced by the alternative aldose reductase pathway active in lens tissue."
    }
