      "D": "Right ventricular outflow tract (RVOT) obstruction could produce a murmur at the left sternal border. However, RVOT obstruction from RV trabeculae hyperplasia is not the mechanism in HCM — HCM predominantly involves asymmetric septal hypertrophy affecting the LEFT ventricular outflow tract. Pulmonic stenosis (most common form of RVOT obstruction) produces a harsh systolic murmur at the upper left sternal border with a widened split of S2, radiation to the back/left shoulder, and associated ECG changes of right heart strain. Pulmonic stenosis murmur does not characteristically increase with Valsalva in the same way as HCM, and pulmonic stenosis is not associated with sudden cardiac death in young athletes. The family history of sudden death in a young relative is the strongest clue to HCM."
