    "correct": "A",
    "explanation": "Sotalol blocks IKr (rapid delayed rectifier potassium channel), prolonging action potential duration and QT interval. The polymorphic ventricular tachycardia twisting around the isoelectric baseline is torsades de pointes. Intravenous magnesium sulfate is first-line treatment — it shortens QT, stabilizes the cardiac membrane, and terminates torsades even without documented hypomagnesemia. Sotalol must be discontinued. Temporary overdrive pacing may be needed for refractory cases.",
    "pearl": "Torsades de pointes: polymorphic VT from long QT. IV magnesium sulfate is first-line (regardless of magnesium level). Stop offending drug. Correct K⁺ and Mg²⁺. Temporary pacing for bradycardia-dependent torsades.",
    "optionExplanations": {
      "A": "Magnesium sulfate is the specific pharmacologic treatment for torsades de pointes. Magnesium works through multiple mechanisms: it shortens the cardiac action potential duration (particularly the vulnerable phase of repolarization), blocks calcium-channel mediated afterdepolarizations (early afterdepolarizations, or EADs, which trigger torsades), and stabilizes the cardiac cell membrane. Critically, magnesium is effective regardless of the serum magnesium level — even patients with normal magnesium benefit from IV magnesium in torsades because its antiarrhythmic mechanism is independent of replenishing a deficiency. The standard dose is 2g IV over 1–2 minutes (can repeat once). Sotalol must be discontinued simultaneously, and any other QT-prolonging drugs removed. Serum potassium should be maintained above 4.5 mEq/L (hypokalemia potentiates IKr block and worsens QT prolongation).",
      "B": "Synchronized cardioversion can terminate torsades de pointes when it degenerates into a hemodynamically unstable rhythm causing hypotension or pulselessness. However, for a hemodynamically STABLE patient with recurrent torsades (as described — syncope with spontaneous termination, stable enough to present to the hospital), synchronized cardioversion alone is inappropriate first-line treatment. Cardioversion terminates individual arrhythmia episodes but does not prevent recurrence from the underlying prolonged QT — sotalol is still in the system and the QT remains dangerously prolonged. IV magnesium addresses the mechanism. Cardioversion is the correct treatment for hemodynamically unstable or sustained torsades; magnesium is for stable/recurrent drug-induced torsades.",
      "C": "Amiodarone is a class III antiarrhythmic that itself blocks IKr and prolongs the QT interval significantly. Administering amiodarone to a patient who already has drug-induced QT prolongation and torsades de pointes would be expected to worsen QT prolongation and potentially provoke additional or more refractory torsades. This is one of the most dangerous drug choices for this scenario. Amiodarone is the correct antiarrhythmic for unstable ventricular tachycardia or ventricular fibrillation (polymorphic VT associated with ischemia), but it is contraindicated in torsades because of its own QT-prolonging properties. Students must distinguish between polymorphic VT caused by long QT (torsades → treat with magnesium, NOT antiarrhythmics) versus polymorphic VT in the setting of normal QT (ischemia-driven → treat with amiodarone and address ischemia).",
      "D": "Adenosine is the first-line treatment for paroxysmal supraventricular tachycardia (PSVT), specifically AV node-dependent reentrant tachycardias — AVNRT and AVRT. Adenosine transiently blocks AV conduction by activating A1 receptors on the AV node, terminating the reentrant loop. Torsades de pointes is a ventricular arrhythmia originating in the ventricles below the AV node — it does not require the AV node as part of its circuit. Adenosine would have no therapeutic effect on torsades and would be ineffective in terminating ventricular arrhythmias of any kind. Additionally, adenosine has an ultra-short half-life (~10 seconds) and even if it briefly changed AV conduction, it would not address the underlying IKr blockade prolonging the QT interval."
    }
