    "testedConcept": "Iron deficiency anemia — low ferritin and elevated TIBC distinguishing from anemia of chronic disease",
    "weakSpotCategory": "Microcytic Anemias",
    "usmleContentArea": "Blood & Lymphoreticular System",
    "usmleSubdomain": "Microcytic Anemia",
    "physicianTask": "Patient Care: Laboratory and Diagnostic Studies",
    "topic": "Microcytic Anemias",
    "questionAngle": "lab-interpretation",
    "memoryAnchor": "IDA: ↓ferritin (most specific), ↓serum Fe, ↑TIBC, ↓transferrin sat (<16%). ACD: normal-↑ferritin, ↓serum Fe, ↓TIBC. Ferritin is acute phase reactant — can be falsely normal in IDA+inflammation.",
    "commonTrap": "Students use only serum iron to diagnose IDA — serum iron is decreased in BOTH IDA and ACD. The key differentiator is TIBC (↑ in IDA, ↓ in ACD) and ferritin (↓ in IDA, normal-↑ in ACD). Ferritin is the most sensitive single test for IDA when not confounded by inflammation.",
    "stem": "A 28-year-old woman with heavy menstrual periods has hemoglobin 8.2 g/dL, MCV 68 fL, MCHC 28 g/dL. Peripheral smear shows microcytic hypochromic RBCs with pencil cells. Which iron study profile best confirms iron deficiency anemia over anemia of chronic disease?",
    "options": [
      {
        "letter": "A",
        "text": "Low ferritin (<12 µg/L) with elevated total iron-binding capacity (TIBC)"
      },
      {
        "letter": "B",
        "text": "Low serum iron with normal TIBC and elevated ferritin"
      },
      {
        "letter": "C",
        "text": "Elevated serum iron with high ferritin and low TIBC"
      },
      {
        "letter": "D",
        "text": "Normal ferritin with low MCV — ferritin is reliable regardless of inflammation"
      }
    ],
    "correct": "A",
    "explanation": "Iron deficiency anemia is most specifically confirmed by low ferritin (<12 µg/L), which reflects depleted body iron stores, combined with elevated total iron-binding capacity (TIBC). When iron stores are depleted, the liver increases transferrin (the protein measured as TIBC) synthesis to scavenge scarce iron. Ferritin <12 µg/L is pathognomonic for iron depletion when not confounded by inflammation (ferritin is an acute phase reactant that can be falsely elevated). Anemia of chronic disease shows normal or elevated ferritin with low or normal TIBC — because iron is trapped in macrophages, not depleted.",
    "pearl": "IDA: ↓ferritin, ↑TIBC, ↓transferrin saturation <16%, microcytic hypochromic anemia. ACD: normal/↑ferritin, ↓TIBC, ↓serum Fe. Treatment of IDA: oral ferrous sulfate (or IV iron if malabsorption). Always identify the underlying source of blood loss.",
    "optionExplanations": {
      "A": "Ferritin <12 µg/L reflects depleted total body iron stores and is the most sensitive and specific single marker for iron deficiency anemia when not confounded by concurrent inflammation (ferritin is a positive acute phase reactant that rises with infection, malignancy, or liver disease). The elevated TIBC reflects increased hepatic transferrin production in response to iron starvation — as intracellular iron falls, SREBP-mediated transferrin gene expression increases. The combination of low ferritin + elevated TIBC + low transferrin saturation (<16%) is the classic diagnostic triad of IDA.",
      "B": "Low serum iron with normal TIBC and elevated ferritin is the classic pattern of anemia of chronic disease (ACD). In ACD, inflammatory cytokines (predominantly IL-6) stimulate hepcidin secretion from the liver, which internalizes ferroportin on macrophages and enterocytes, trapping iron intracellularly. The result: serum iron falls (exported iron is blocked), ferritin rises (macrophage iron storage increases), and TIBC is reduced or normal (hepatic transferrin production is not stimulated because intracellular iron is actually abundant).",
      "C": "Elevated serum iron with high ferritin and low TIBC describes iron overload states — hereditary hemochromatosis (autosomal recessive, HFE gene mutation), transfusional hemosiderosis, or sideroblastic anemia. In hereditary hemochromatosis, transferrin saturation exceeds 45–50%. This pattern is the direct opposite of iron deficiency and would not produce microcytic anemia from iron depletion; hemochromatosis causes organ damage from iron deposition (liver fibrosis, cardiomyopathy, diabetes).",
      "D": "Normal ferritin does NOT rule out iron deficiency anemia when concurrent inflammation, infection, or liver disease is present. Ferritin is an acute phase reactant — its level rises with inflammatory states, potentially masking true iron depletion. A patient with iron deficiency anemia and concurrent rheumatoid arthritis or chronic infection may have a ferritin level that falls within the \"normal\" laboratory range while iron stores are actually depleted. In this setting, soluble transferrin receptor (sTfR) level or bone marrow biopsy may be needed."
    }
