    "topic": "Movement Disorder Pharmacology",
    "questionAngle": "pharmacology",
    "memoryAnchor": "Parkinson: TRAP (Tremor at rest, Rigidity, Akinesia/bradykinesia, Postural instability). Loss of dopaminergic neurons in substantia nigra pars compacta. Levodopa+carbidopa (DOPA decarboxylase inhibitor) = mainstay. Carbidopa prevents peripheral conversion → more L-DOPA reaches brain.",
    "commonTrap": "Students think dopamine is given directly — dopamine cannot cross the blood-brain barrier. Levodopa (L-DOPA) crosses the BBB and is converted to dopamine in the brain. Carbidopa inhibits peripheral DOPA decarboxylase, preventing conversion before BBB, maximizing CNS delivery and reducing nausea.",
    "stem": "A 68-year-old man has a resting tremor of the right hand (pill-rolling), cogwheel rigidity, masked facies, and shuffling gait with reduced arm swing. He tends to stoop and has difficulty initiating movement. His cognition is intact. Which pharmacologic strategy best addresses the underlying pathophysiology?",
    "options": [
      {
        "letter": "A",
        "text": "Levodopa combined with carbidopa to increase dopamine in the basal ganglia"
      },
      {
        "letter": "B",
        "text": "Haloperidol to block dopamine D2 receptors and reduce motor hyperactivity"
      },
      {
        "letter": "C",
        "text": "Bromocriptine alone without levodopa to avoid dyskinesias from the outset"
      },
      {
        "letter": "D",
        "text": "Intravenous dopamine infusion to replenish dopaminergic neurotransmission"
      }
    ],
    "correct": "A",
    "explanation": "Parkinson disease results from degeneration of dopaminergic neurons in the substantia nigra pars compacta, reducing dopamine input to the striatum and disrupting the basal ganglia motor circuit. Levodopa combined with carbidopa is the most effective pharmacotherapy. Levodopa (L-DOPA) crosses the blood-brain barrier and is converted to dopamine in residual nigrostriatal neurons. Carbidopa inhibits peripheral aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase (DOPA decarboxylase), preventing peripheral conversion of levodopa to dopamine — which cannot re-enter the CNS — thereby increasing CNS dopamine delivery and reducing peripheral side effects (nausea, vomiting). Haloperidol worsens parkinsonism by blocking D2 receptors.",
    "pearl": "Parkinson pharmacology: Levodopa+carbidopa = most effective (carbidopa blocks peripheral DOPA decarboxylase). MAO-B inhibitors (selegiline, rasagiline): adjunct, neuroprotective potential. COMT inhibitors (entacapone): prolong levodopa effect. Dopamine agonists (pramipexole): younger patients to delay dyskinesias. Avoid antipsychotics (worsen parkinsonism).",
    "optionExplanations": {
      "A": "Levodopa is the immediate precursor of dopamine that can cross the blood-brain barrier via the large neutral amino acid transporter. Once in the CNS, residual dopaminergic neurons (and glia) convert levodopa to dopamine via DOPA decarboxylase. Carbidopa is a peripheral DOPA decarboxylase inhibitor that does not cross the BBB — it blocks peripheral conversion of levodopa to dopamine, preventing most of the nausea and cardiovascular effects of peripheral dopamine while maximizing the amount of levodopa reaching the CNS. The combination typically allows 75–80% dose reduction in levodopa while improving efficacy.",
      "B": "Haloperidol is a typical antipsychotic that blocks D2 dopamine receptors in the striatum. Reducing dopaminergic activity in a patient with Parkinson disease — which already has dopamine deficiency — would dramatically worsen all motor symptoms (tremor, rigidity, bradykinesia). Drug-induced parkinsonism from antipsychotics is one of the most common causes of secondary parkinsonism. All typical antipsychotics and many atypical antipsychotics (except quetiapine and clozapine) are contraindicated in Parkinson disease.",
      "C": "Bromocriptine and other dopamine agonists (pramipexole, ropinirole) act directly on postsynaptic D2/D3 receptors and are useful for early Parkinson disease in younger patients to delay the dyskinesias associated with long-term levodopa therapy. However, dopamine agonists are less effective than levodopa for motor symptom control, particularly as disease advances. Monotherapy with dopamine agonists is not the most effective initial strategy for a symptomatic patient — levodopa with carbidopa provides superior motor control, especially for a 68-year-old where dyskinesia timing concerns are less pressing.",
      "D": "Intravenous dopamine cannot cross the blood-brain barrier due to its hydrophilic, charged structure at physiologic pH. Peripheral dopamine infusion acts on cardiovascular dopamine receptors (D1 at high doses on vasculature, renal dopamine receptors) but produces no CNS dopaminergic effect. IV dopamine is used in hemodynamic management of shock — not in neurological conditions. This distractor tests whether students understand the BBB selectivity that requires the levodopa prodrug strategy."
    }
